This paper deals with the computational complexity of computing Nash equilibria in bimatrix games, which is a topic in game theory. Therefore, cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves reductions and complexity classes such as PPAD, which are common in computational complexity theory, making cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also mentions linear programming and approximation algorithms, which are topics in artificial intelligence and optimization, respectively, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves combinatorial and graph-theoretic arguments, which are common in discrete mathematics, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) a possible sub-category as well.
